Their worst feature, however, was after all not the oppressive procedure ol the trial, but the encouragement given to private animosity or greed, through the practice os allowing prosecu- . tions to be inaugurated by private individuals, who were to receive a certain proportion of the fines and confiscations as their reward. That Tiberius insisted strongly upon the neces- sity ol employing and rewarding delations by private persons (I. 72, IV. 30), has been a leading reproach against him. It is not always noticed, however, that he gave his reason sor this, in the fact that the delations were an essential part os the machinery for criminal justice, and that without them crimes would go unpunished. In truth, the fault was a fundamental one in the Roman judicial system, and the real short-coming of Tiberius was, not in putting in execution the existing machinÎ‡ ery, but in not devising some more efficient machinery.
